
DAILYDIFF.DEV
Project Plan
A daily curriculum delivery system for software engineers
Removes the decision fatigue of interview prep

May 2026
Side Project  ·  v1.0

1. Executive Summary
What is DailyDiff?
A daily email that tells software engineers exactly what to study today: 2–3 DSA problems + 1 curated engineering article. Not a content newsletter — a delivery mechanism for a structured curriculum that removes the daily decision cost of “what should I work on?”


The Problem
Software engineers typically start interview preparation only when they decide to switch jobs. They relearn everything from scratch each time. The issue is not a lack of resources — Leetcode, NeetCode, and engineering blogs are abundant. The real problem is decision fatigue at the start of each study session. When faced with 150 problems and 50 blogs, most people either pick something too easy, spend 30 minutes planning instead of doing, or skip the session entirely.
The Insight
Leetcode’s daily problem works because it removes choice. But it’s one random problem with no progression. DailyDiff applies the same mechanic to a structured curriculum: problems are sequenced by topic and difficulty, articles are paired thematically, and the reader just opens and does. Even completing 3 out of 7 daily plans is meaningful progress.
Key Properties
Not content creation: DailyDiff aggregates and sequences existing resources. It redirects to Leetcode, to the original blog. No original articles to write.
Automated after setup: The content DB is built once. A scheduling algorithm picks daily items. Marginal cost per issue is near-zero.
Newsletter as UX: Email is the delivery wrapper. The product is the opinionated daily plan.


2. Competitive Landscape
The engineering newsletter space is crowded, but DailyDiff competes on a different axis. The incumbents are content products (original writing, insights, analysis). DailyDiff is a scheduling product (sequenced curriculum delivered via email).

Competitor
What they do
How DailyDiff differs
Pragmatic Engineer
Original long-form essays on engineering culture, 1M+ subscribers
Content brand with a voice. DailyDiff has no voice — it’s a plan, not a read.
ByteByteGo
System design deep-dives + visual explainers, 1M+ subscribers
Educational content. DailyDiff doesn’t teach — it assigns.
Leetcode Daily
One random problem per day, same for everyone
Closest analog. But it’s random, isolated, and has no progression or article pairing.
NeetCode / Roadmap.sh
Curated lists and roadmaps (Blind 75, NeetCode 150)
Shows the map but doesn’t tell you what to do on Tuesday morning. DailyDiff fills that gap.
Tech Interview Daily
Daily leetcode patterns + system design frameworks
Content-heavy newsletter. DailyDiff is link-only — no original writing, just assignments.


The positioning gap
DailyDiff sits between Leetcode’s daily problem (too random, no progression) and NeetCode’s roadmap (too static, no daily cadence). It’s the daily plan that neither provides.



3. Product Design
What the reader receives
Each morning at 7am IST, the subscriber gets an email with three sections:

Section
Content
Example
DSA
2–3 Leetcode problems, sequenced by topic week and progressive difficulty
→ Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters (Medium, ~20m)→ Minimum Window Substring (Hard, ~35m)
READ
1 curated engineering blog article, paired thematically with the DSA topic
→ How Cloudflare Sizes Connection Pools (Cloudflare Engineering, ~12m)
CONTEXT
1–2 sentences on why these pair together and what pattern to notice
Both problems are sliding-window with a hashmap. The Cloudflare piece is the same idea at infrastructure scale.


Frequency
Daily, Monday through Friday. The reader is not expected to complete every day. The design principle is: even doing 3 out of 7 is progress. Missed days are not penalized. No streaks, no guilt, no “you missed 4 days!” emails. The plan keeps moving.
What DailyDiff does NOT do
Write original content or commentary beyond the 1–2 sentence context line
Host or reproduce problem statements (links redirect to Leetcode)
Track per-user progress (V1 — everyone gets the same issue)
Offer a paid tier, courses, or premium content


4. Naming & Brand
Name: dailydiff
“Diff” is the engineer’s word for “what changed.” It works on two levels: the daily code diff (what’s new in your skills) and the Unix diff command (a precise, minimal delta). The name signals the audience (engineers), the cadence (daily), and the product mechanic (incremental change) in two words.
Domain: dailydiff.dev
The .dev TLD is Google-owned, HTTPS-enforced by default, and signals “for developers” at the domain level. It was chosen over .com (likely taken or expensive for this two-word combo) and .xyz (worse spam reputation, which matters for a daily email product where deliverability is the whole game).
Why not “the” dailydiff?
Shorter: two fewer syllables when spoken aloud, three fewer characters in URLs, emails, and handles
Cleaner handles: @dailydiff reads better than @thedailydiff on Twitter/GitHub/Substack
Avoids brand confusion: “The Diff” by Byrne Hobart is a well-known tech/finance newsletter with 50K+ subscribers. Dropping “the” creates clear separation
The article adds nothing: “DailyDiff” is already a distinctive compound noun. It doesn’t need a definite article the way generic words (“The Hustle”, “The Verge”) do
Handles to register
On the day the domain is purchased: @dailydiff on Twitter/X, GitHub, Substack, Bluesky, and beehiiv. All free. Squatters grab newsletter-adjacent names.


5. Content Pipeline
Overview
The content pipeline has two halves: capture (how links get into the database) and scheduling (how links get picked for each daily issue). The capture half uses Obsidian as the staging area and Postgres as the publication source. You curate naturally in your existing note-taking flow; a cron job handles the rest.
5.1 Capture: Obsidian → Postgres Pipe
Architecture
Obsidian notes are markdown files in a folder on disk. The pipe is a Go script that walks the vault folder, parses YAML frontmatter from each .md file, and upserts the data into Postgres. No API, no plugin, no sync service — just a file walk.

Vault structure:
~/ObsidianVault/Articles/*.md — curated blog articles
~/ObsidianVault/DSA-Problems/*.md — DSA problem links

Frontmatter contract (articles)
Each article note uses YAML frontmatter that maps 1:1 to the articles database table. The body of the note can contain personal reading notes — the pipe ignores it.

Field
Type
Purpose
url
string
Canonical URL of the article (used as the primary key via hash)
title
string
Article title
source
string
Engineering blog name (e.g., “netflix_tech”, “stripe_engineering”)
topics
array
Topic tags: [“distributed_systems”, “caching”]
depth
enum
One of: intro, intermediate, deep_dive
estimated_minutes
integer
Approximate read time
published_at
date
The article’s original publication date
status
enum
draft | ready | archived — only “ready” items are piped to the DB
notes
string
Your own one-liner takeaway (optional)


The status field
status: ready is the kill switch. The pipe skips any note without this value. This means you can clip an article into Obsidian, read it later, and only tag it ready once you’ve confirmed it’s worth including. No half-read articles accidentally show up in tomorrow’s newsletter.
Primary key strategy
Use a hash of the url field as the primary key. URLs are stable; filenames can change (if you rename a note, the pipe would otherwise think it’s a new article). This handles 95% of cases and requires zero discipline beyond filling in the url field.
Idempotency
INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (url_hash) DO UPDATE SET ... — the pipe is safe to re-run any number of times. New article = inserted. Edited frontmatter = updated. Unchanged = no-op.
Deletion handling
Soft delete with a 7-day grace period. If a URL disappears from all Obsidian notes for 7 consecutive runs, mark it archived in the DB. This protects against accidental file deletions while still allowing intentional removal.

5.2 Content Database
Scale constraints
These numbers define the upper bound of the system. Anything beyond them is unrealistic for a side project:

Data type
Max records
Rationale
DSA problem links
5,000
The universe of Leetcode 75/150/Blind 75/Striver’s sheets is ~2–3K. 5K is generous headroom.
Article links
100,000
50 engineering blogs × 2,000 posts each = 100K. Aggressive but bounded.
Daily newsletter history
2,000
1 issue/day × 365 × 5 years = 1,825. Rounds to 2K.
Custom newsletter records
10,000/year
Only relevant if per-user tracks are built (V2+).


Total data: under 200K rows across all tables. A single Postgres instance on any machine handles this without breaking a sweat for the next decade. No sharding, no caching layer, no queue, no microservices.

Schema: 5 tables
The database has five tables. The first three are core; the last two are optional and should be deferred.

