6. System Architecture
Overview
The entire system is three components and two cron jobs. No microservices, no queue, no caching layer.

Minimal architecture
[Postgres] ← [Admin scripts / Obsidian pipe to add content]
    ↓
[Daily cron at 6am IST] → builds today’s issue → writes to newsletter_issues
    ↓
[Send cron at 7am IST] → reads today’s issue → POSTs to Loops API → marks sent


What you do NOT need
A separate users/auth system — Loops handles signup
A tags table with many-to-many joins — Postgres array columns + GIN indexes are fine at this scale
A queue (SQS/Redis/etc) — a single cron job is enough; if sending fails, retry tomorrow
Caching — reads are 1–2 queries per day from a cron; there is nothing to cache
Search infrastructure (Elasticsearch, Meilisearch) — with 100K rows, Postgres ILIKE queries are fine
Analytics DB — Loops provides opens/clicks; that’s enough
Hosting plan
Component
Where
Cost
Postgres
Local MacBook M3 Pro (V1), then $5/mo VPS when ready to ship
$0 → $5/mo
Cron jobs
launchd on Mac (V1), then same VPS
$0
Email sending
Loops (existing account from Munshiji)
Free tier
Domain + DNS
Cloudflare
~$12/yr for .dev
Total


$0 to ~$5/mo



7. Scheduling Algorithm
The scheduler is the actual product. Everything else (the DB, the email, the landing page) is plumbing. This is where the quality of the daily plan is determined.
Daily scheduler steps (6am cron)
Look at the last 7–14 issues to determine which topics were covered recently
Determine today’s topic based on the curriculum’s progression model (e.g., 4 weeks of arrays/strings, 2 weeks of trees, etc.)
Pick 2–3 DSA problems matching that topic, with at least one being a difficulty step up from yesterday
Pick 1 article that pairs thematically (e.g., a system design article on “rate limiting” goes well with DSA week on “sliding window”)
Write the issue row to newsletter_issues

Scheduling constraints
Topic progression: follow a predefined curriculum order, not random sampling
Spacing: don’t put 3 hard DP problems back-to-back
Topic cycling: don’t serve 5 days of trees in a row
Difficulty ramp: at least one problem should be harder than the previous day’s median
Article–DSA pairing: surface articles that share conceptual DNA with the day’s problems

Start dumb, add sophistication later
Begin with random selection within constraints and add intelligence only when you notice patterns that annoy you as a user yourself. The scheduler will improve over time as you use your own product.



8. System Flow (End-to-End)
The full pipeline from reading an article to a subscriber receiving it. Refer to the Excalidraw diagram for the visual version.


Phase 1: Capture (your daily habit)
You read an article in your browser
Obsidian Web Clipper extension creates a .md note in your vault
Note lands in ~/Vault/Articles/ with auto-filled URL and title
You add frontmatter: topics, depth, and status: ready to mark it shippable

Phase 2: Pipe (automated, 3am cron)
launchd triggers your Go script on the MacBook
Walker lists all .md files in Articles/ and DSA-Problems/
Frontmatter parser reads each file, skips if status ≠ ready
UPSERT by url-hash into Postgres (idempotent, safe to re-run)

Phase 3: Schedule & Send (automated, 6–7am cron)
Scheduler queries the DB for candidate items based on curriculum rules
Applies constraints (topic progression, difficulty ramp, spacing)
Writes the picked items as a row in newsletter_issues
Renders to HTML and POSTs to Loops API as a campaign
Subscriber receives it in inbox at 7am IST

Key property
Steps 1–4 are your daily habit (reading + tagging in Obsidian, which you’d do anyway). Steps 5–14 are fully automated. You never log into a database, never write a newsletter from scratch.



