What NOT to monetize
Don’t gate the daily email behind a paywall — the product’s value is the daily delivery; paywalling it defeats the purpose
Don’t sell subscriber data
Don’t add a second email per day for sponsors


10. Marketing
Launch channels
Twitter/X: threads on DSA prep, engineering blog discoveries, the “why I built this” story
LinkedIn: same content, formatted for the feed (carousels, short posts)
Reddit: r/cscareerquestions, r/leetcode, r/experienceddevs — genuine participation first, then share
Indian engineering communities: you’re in Bengaluru — the Indian SWE prep market is enormous and underserved by English-language newsletters
Lead magnet ideas
A PDF cheat sheet: “The 20 Leetcode patterns you need, mapped to real system design concepts”
A Notion/Obsidian template for the frontmatter schema (meta: helps people build their own version, builds goodwill)
Retention over acquisition
The actual marketing problem isn’t getting subscribers — it’s keeping them. Two design choices that help:
Don’t shame missed days. No “you missed 4 days!” emails. Those make people unsubscribe rather than re-engage.
Make catching up trivially optional. “Yesterday’s problem” link in today’s email, not a guilt trip.


11. Build Plan
Phase 1: Foundation (Week 1–2)
Set up Postgres locally (brew install postgresql)
Define the three core tables (dsa_problems, articles, newsletter_issues)
Manually add 50 DSA problems and 20 articles to validate the schema feels right
Set up pg_dump backup cron: weekly to ~/backups/
Phase 2: Pipe (Week 3)
Write the Go frontmatter parser as a one-shot script (stdout first, no DB)
Add 5–10 real article notes in Obsidian with the full frontmatter schema
Use the schema for a few days — see if any fields are annoying to fill out, adjust
Connect to Postgres, implement the upsert logic
Wrap in a launchd job to run nightly
Phase 3: Scheduler (Week 4)
Write the scheduler script in Go
Start with simple random selection within topic/difficulty constraints
Have it generate 7 days of issues into the DB
Review the output manually — does the sequence feel right?
Phase 4: Ship (Week 5)
Wire up Loops integration (POST campaign API)
Register domain (dailydiff.dev) + handles (@dailydiff everywhere)
Build landing page (email signup → Loops)
Send the first issue to yourself only, then to 10 friends for feedback
Phase 5: Launch (Week 6)
Open the waitlist
Announce on Twitter, LinkedIn, and one relevant subreddit
Ship the first public issue

3-month checkpoint
If you haven’t hit 200 subscribers AND you’re not enjoying it, kill it without guilt. Side projects that drag on past their expiration date are worse than ones that get shut down cleanly.



12. Risks & Mitigations
Risk
Severity
Mitigation
Curriculum quality is poor (problems feel random, topics repeat)
High
Spend more time on the scheduling algorithm than you think. This is the product.
Email deliverability degrades (daily emails get flagged as spam)
Medium
Monitor open rates weekly. If they drop below 25%, investigate. Use Loops’ warm-up features.
You burn out on content curation
Medium
Obsidian pipe means curation happens naturally as you read. Not a separate chore.
Leetcode changes URLs or structure
Low
URL-hash as primary key means the DB is resilient. Broken links can be caught with a monthly health-check script.
Mac must be on at 3am for the pipe
Low
Use launchd’s “run on next wake” option. Or sync vault to a VPS later.




